,"title":"Reply","footer":1},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8607089#t8607089","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8607089#t8607089","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8607089#t8607089","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"daveax","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://daveax.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":8607089,"talkid":33621,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8607089#t8607089","upictitle":"daveax: Cthulhu","article":"A number of her books have been published in limited editions by the good folks at Subterranean Press. I dunno if there's any left by now, but this would certainly be a good time to check if you want 'em.","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"7 years ago","ctime":"February 6 2010, 17:28:23 UTC","massactions":0,"subject":"","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://daveax.livejournal.com/","striked":null,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"daveax","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"daveax","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://daveax.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"daveax","ctime_ts":1265477303,"tracked":0},{"shown":1,"collapsed":0,"userpic":"http://l-userpic.livejournal.com/98567651/25231307","actions":[{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?replyto=8608625","name":"reply","title":"Reply","footer":1},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8608625#t8608625","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8608625#t8608625","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8608625#t8608625","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"prof_nrvna","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://prof-nrvna.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":8608625,"talkid":33627,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8608625#t8608625","upictitle":"prof_nrvna: pic#98567651","article":"I had just read her book \"Anvil of the World\" over the summer. I really enjoyed it; it was a really unique take on the fantasy genre, interesting and fast paced without relying on cliches. ","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"7 years ago","ctime":"February 6 2010, 23:00:12 UTC","massactions":0,"subject":"Oh no, really?","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://prof-nrvna.livejournal.com/","striked":null,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"prof_nrvna","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"prof_nrvna","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://prof-nrvna.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"prof_nrvna","ctime_ts":1265497212,"tracked":0},{"shown":1,"collapsed":0,"actions":[{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?replyto=8668017","name":"reply","title":"Reply","footer":1},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8668017#t8668017","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8668017#t8668017","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8668017#t8668017","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"medievaleurope","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://medievaleurope.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":8668017,"talkid":33859,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/131185.html?thread=8668017#t8668017","upictitle":"medievaleurope: pic#0","article":"Having watched my Dad die of cancer this past year, I can attest to the sadness it leaves behind. I learned a lot from that experience, about myself and about life. Specifically, I learned that I cannot continue to put off goals that I have held since high school (ten years ago). So, I am now working on my own fantasy series, one set in Medieval Europe with a high-fantasy feel.<br />Whereas my Dad's death inspired me to get my butt in gear, your writing has inspired me to write a fantasy series that goes beyond the \"sword and sorcery\" which is so often attached to fantasy in general. Although you write in a different genre, I think of you as the Isaac Asimov of Fantasy. <br />Asimov drew readers in with his attentiveness to human nature and its relationship with technology. Asimov did not need an endless series of action sequences to keep readers focussed. The same can be said of your series, I believe. I thoroughly enjoy how your characters are not wholly good or evil. Instead, they are simply human, which makes them more endearing and real.<br />Just as Asimov used science fiction as a commentary on the relationship between humanity and technology, I believe your Song of Ice and Fire series is a commentary on humanity's relationship with power.<br />While studying for my masters degree in military histoy years ago, I came to realize that human nature has changed very little. We will always have moral martyrs like Eddard, innocents like Sansa (an innocence soon lost I dare to presume?), beasts like Gregor (I cannot name Sandor, for I believe that he was more knightly than many other knights in your books and in history), social outcasts like Brienne and Tyrion, and many more.<br />I've read few works of fiction that make me empathize with the characters in question the way I empathize with humanity when reading historical non-fiction, so thank you for creating a fantasy series filled with detailed and flawed characters that grow before our eyes.<br />I eagerly await A Dance of Dragons. I know you must get many emails full of anger for having to wait so long for the completion of Dragons, but I have no problem waiting even ten years to read the gem that Dragons is likely to be, and I am sure many others feel the same.<br />Good luck!","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"7 years ago","ctime":"February 9 2010, 21:19:21 UTC","massactions":0,"subject":"Cancer","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://medievaleurope.livejournal.com/","striked":1,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"medievaleurope","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"medievaleurope","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://medievaleurope.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"medievaleurope","ctime_ts":1265750361,"tracked":0}]}